entry.title: Reland: Recalculate style before setting ICB size for printing.
entry.content:
One change, compared to the initial attempt: Set zero page margins in

the browser test, to avoid crbug.com/1491775



Original commit comment follows:



A zoom factor used when viewing a webpage on screen may have been set in

computed style. This would affect @page margin resolution incorrectly

when entering print mode, which in turn would result in an incorrect

initial containing block size. To fix this, recalculate style before

calculating the page area size.



Since we now recalculate style before setting any initial containing

block size for printing at all, viewport units will not be resolved

correctly. So make sure that they get calculated before laying out. This

used to be triggered by calling LayoutViewportWasResized(). It turns out

though, now that we need to do this unconditionally before the first

layout, that LayoutViewportWasResized() does more than we want. For

printing, we don't need to re-evaluate media queries, and we do not want

a resize event to be fired. Therefore, split the viewport units dirtying

into a separate function. Introduce a lambda in

ForceLayoutForPagination() to avoid repetitive code.



Make PrintBrowserTest.NoResizeEvent more evil, by modifying its resource

HTML file to use a named page, and also a wide DIV. This would make the

test fail without this CL.



Add external/wpt/css/printing/ to the scalefactor200 virtual test suite.

Three other tests (the already existing page-margin-xxx tests) would

also fail without this fix, but add a test for this specific issue

(abspos) as well.

entry.title: Support mask-clip values: <geometry-box> and no-clip
entry.content:
This patch wires up and implements the specified behavior for

and no-clip values on the mask-clip property, which is

behind the CSSMaskingInterop flag.



Spec: https://drafts.fxtf.org/css-masking/#the-mask-clip



With this patch, we now support the following on boxes:

mask-clip: margin-box; (new!)

mask-clip: no-clip; (new!)

mask-clip: fill-box; (equivalent to content-box)

mask-clip: stroke-box; (equivalent to border-box)

mask-clip: view-box; (equivalent to border-box)



The implementation for margin-box and no-clip could use some

elaborating. There are two code changes:

1. CSSMaskPainter::MaskBoundingBox is used for property trees and now

uses a larger clip for margin-box and no-clip.

2. BackgroundImageGeometry::ComputeDestRectAdjustments now returns an

adjustment for margin-box and no-clip that is inflated. For margin-box,

this approach is important because we need to clip to the rounded

border radius created by the margin-box clip. No-clip follows the same

pattern for consistency.



Bug: 1418401

entry.content:

CameraAppHelperImpl, and the other is CameraAppDeviceImpl. CCA uses

CameraAppHelperImpl to check the document scanner status and uses

CameraAppDeviceImpl to do the ml method calls via mojo. Since

CheckDocumentModeReadiness will never be called by CameraAppDeviceImpl,

LoadDocumentScanner needs to be executed in constructor of

DocumentScannerServiceClient to support ML service like corner detection

in CCA.

entry.title: Implement fallback to kSharedMemory if kGpuMemoryBuffer is not NV12.
entry.content:
Some virtual cameras create non-MJPEG and non-NV12 sample buffers that

does not have a pixel buffer and as such VideoCaptureDeviceAVFoundation

is unable to produce GPU NV12 buffers. This triggers DCHECKs and a

NOTREACHED down in media::GpuMemoryBufferTrackerApple::Init() if the

target buffer type is configured to kGpuMemoryBuffer, since our code

base assumes that GPU buffers are NV12 on macOS.



The same fix that currently exists for a similar Windows situation is

extended to macOS, since falling back to kSharedMemory is better than

DCHECK-crashing and dropping frames.



Because verifying the fix requires a weird setup, the fix is landed

behind flag (FallbackToSharedMemoryIfNotNv12). This will allow us to

manually verify the fix on Canary on one of the test machines before

enabling it by default.

entry.title: ServiceWorkerAutoPreload Fix the potential crash in fallback edge case
entry.content:
This CL fixes the crash error that can happen when SWAutoPreload handles

the fetch handler and the result is fallback. Specifically, this can

the response. However, the request may not finish yet and thus

`completion_status_` may not be set. `completion_status_` is used in

`CompleteResponse()`, and that may cause the crash.

entry.title: dlp: CopyOrMove shouldn't progress if cancelled
entry.content:
Adds a check in CopyOrMoveIOTaskImpl::OnCheckIfTransferAllowed() for

the task's state and aborts if the task was cancelled.



CopyOrMoveIOTask-s Cancel() method does not actually cancel any actions,

but rather we rely on the IOTaskController-s Cancel() method to remove

the unique_ptr to the IO task, thus destroying the object and cancelling

the in-flight operations if necessary. However, if this doesn't happen

fast enough, like on linux-chromeos-dbg builders, the task continues

executing even after being cancelled. The could even task send an

InProgress status update before being destroyed. This was caught only on

dbg builders because we expected the notifications to get closed after we "click" on them - however, a new "Copying..." notification would get

shown and fail the test.

entry.title: siso: support chromeos simplechrome flow
entry.content:
Change filegroups to take ctx, so that cros.star can define

filegroups for toolchain, sysroots defined by gn args.

It requires siso v0.0.17 (git_revision:c689f99bb4b9908073bd2f3fbd68f289d9e45a75 or later).



cros compile uses -fprofile-sample-use=*.prof.

The profile data file *.prof is listed in inputs of cc/cxx action,

but siso ignores it in favor of deps.

Using cc/cxx's inputs in siso seems the right solution, but

some cc/cxx's action depends on *.inputdeps.stamp, which depends on

*.prof file. To capture such inputs, we could use ExpandedInputs

of step.def, but it would capture lots of unnecessary files as

remote exec inputs (e.g. *.pak, *pak.info etc), and requires lots

of siso's memory.

To mitigate the issue, cros_compiler handlers check command line

and add *.prof when -fprofile-samle-use= is used.
